<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>October 2013</title></head><body style="background:#ffffff"><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Friends of the Earth</span></p><p style="font-size:20pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Rapid and extensive action is required in England to restore biodiversity and ecosystems function.  This is not best secured by allowing for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tradeable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> destruction of habitats. Nature is too complex to simply be moved at the whim of a developer.  Some ancient habitats are impossible to recreate and many others difficult to restore.  Nature has an intrinsic value that cannot be measured and access to the natural world is valuable to local communities – that value is lost if nature is shifted to another part of the country.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other means of securing restoration should be given preference.  The Government should strengthen the commitment to biodiversity gain through the planning system; ensure better use of public funds through the Common Agricultural Policy to boost biodiversity on farmland; and improve management of wildlife sites.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no convincing evidence that biodiversity offsetting is an effective way to  protect and restore biodiversity.  The experience from other countries is mixed and the UK offset pilots are not yet complete making any early introduction of offsetting in the UK premature.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Offfsetting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> has significant risks including that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Instead of gains for biodiversity it could simply facilitate greater destruction of nature in areas of high development pressure in return for a promise of  habitat creation where land is cheaper.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Important and unique  habitats could be lost forever.  Biodiversity is often irreplaceable especially ancient woodland, ancient meadows and soils,  New sites will not contain the same features as existing habitats, and reintroducing biodiversity is fraught with problems.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Developers will have less incentive to incorporate proper space for nature into new development as they may instead decide to pay for biodiversity in another location.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">People’s access to nature will not be valued yet this is vital to communities whether or not it is regarded as ‘distinctive’ by some measure invented by policy makers and organisations with a vested interest in offsetting.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Measuring the value of natural capital and ecosystem function is complex and is not fully reflected in any of the current proposed metrics for offsetting – e.g. the value of services provided by nature such as pollination or flood mitigation are not captured. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Failure to secure the provision of offset sites and their long term management would result in overall loss of biodiversity.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodiversity offsetting is a market-based tool that assesses loss of biodiversity in a development scheme and requires the loss to be replaced elsewhere.  Proposals for offsetting in the UK were included in the 2011 Natural Environment White Paper and a series of offsetting pilots were set up.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsetting is – at best - no more than a tool for delivering compensation for damage to biodiversity where after all other options have been exhausted that damage is considered unavoidable. But offsetting is now being touted as something that will deliver biodiversity gain on a grand scale.  I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n March 2013 the business-led Ecosystems Market Task Force (EMTF) claimed that offsetting would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">revolutionise conservation in England” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and urged Government to introduce a mandatory scheme.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra issued a Green Paper in September 2013 stating that it wants to set out “detailed proposals” for offsetting by the end of 2013.  Yet no evidence from the pilots has yet been published by Defra to demonstrate that offsetting delivers benefits to biodiversity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Achieving Biodiversity Gain in Planning Policy</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In England, the National Planning Policy Framework (NPPF) states that the planning system should minimise impacts on biodiversity, provide net gain in biodiversity and establish coherent ecological networks.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NPPF already requires that compensation should be used as a last resort at the bottom of a hierarchy that puts avoidance and mitigation first.  Where compensation for biodiversity loss is not possible the NPPF states that planning permission should be refused. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a need for improving mitigation and compensation through the planning system</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but it does not follow that a new market-based system is needed. Indeed it is unclear how offsetting would overcome existing problems in providing compensation through the planning system.  These include little attempt to avoid the damage; poor assessment of existing sites and so of damage and compensation required; lack of enforcement,  and inadequate monitoring of mitigation and compensation measures. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government should strengthen the commitment to biodiversity gain through the existing planning system.  It needs be much clearer (for example in new Planning Practice Guidance) that biodiversity gain is an essential part of the definition of sustainable development – so that the presumption in favour of development does not apply if biodiversity gain is not demonstrable .  Important wildlife sites must be taken into account in housing land availability assessments.  And clear guidance is needed on how Local Plans must identify and map important sites for protection and set out a strategy for habitat creation and connectivity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The NPPF is unlikely to deliver gains for biodiversity while there remains in place a clear emphasis on economic growth over environmental protection.  This emphasis increases the risk that offsetting would simply help to facilitate inappropriate development especially in areas of high development pressure.  The recognition that nature is actually underpins our economy and wellbeing must be better acknowledged in planning policy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of Evidence that Offsetting works</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it is not at all clear that international use of offsetting makes the case for its adoption in the UK.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9.5pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Green Paper uses the offsetting scheme in Victoria, Australia as a positive case study of offsetting.  Yet few empirical studies of the effectiveness of biodiversity offsets have been undertaken in Australia. A 2010 study of habitat offsets in Western Victoria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“it is unlikely that offsets (for large scattered trees) would achieve a no net loss’ (neutralising) effect and at best long-term decline could be minimised by certain offsetting strategies”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The longest historic exercise in the use of offsetting mechanisms operates in the context of wetland loss in the US,  Evaluation has found that wetland mitigation is at best  problematic  and  for important criteria such as ecosystem function are not delivering no net loss. </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are 6 offset pilots in the UK due to finish in April 2014.  It would be premature to consider introducing offsetting before these have been thoroughly assessed.  Even then it is questionable whether the pilots have generated enough offsetting activity or have run for long enough to offer any meaningful results.  The Environmental Policy Forum referred to the two year timescale as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“woefully short”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> given the time it takes for any natural habitat to become properly established</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Risks of Biodiversity Offsetting</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Nature is unique and complex and cannot simply be replaced.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Habitats are unique and nature has an intrinsic value irrespective of its rarity or distinctiveness. Richard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Benyon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> MP, former Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for the Environment and Fisheries</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> stated that offsetting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would not be a case of ‘comparing the value of an otter against the value of a hedgehog’.  But the use of offsetting implicitly means a trade-off between habitats and species.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consultation paper puts forward the idea of a ‘free-trading system’ where any type of habitat could be provided as an offset as long as it generates “sufficient biodiversity units”.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some habitats would require 'like for like' compensation.  But replacing an established habitat e.g. a hedgerow with new planting is not 'like for like' because of the time it takes for species to become established. Applying a standard multiplier to take account of establishment time seems a very crude approach. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The timescales required to restore habitats to fully functioning ecosystems, and ensure no net loss is one of the evidence gaps that ecologists have highlighted in the current offsetting proposals.  The lack of accounting for below-ground diversity, the extremely long timescales involved in restoring below ground diversity and effects this has on ecosystem functioning are a particular concern</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.The risks and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clunkiness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of offsetting as a prime tool for nature conservation also apply to species. For instance how would offsetting properly account for all 267 species of British bee, some especially vulnerable and confined to ever decreasing patches of the country because their habitats, food sources and conditions have been damaged and removed from the rest of the country.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Data on many species  is poor raising the question of how a developer or local authority will be able to assess what it is that they need to replace.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Even where species are specifically protected success in restoration has  proved difficult.  A study in France found that  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“species richness was much lower in offset sites” </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biodiversity gain will not be delivered </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a risk that offsetting will be seen as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">way to fund nature restoration at the expense of more effective use of  public funds and strengthening of policy and regulations. To  build the mosaic essential to a healthy and functioning ecosystem, as envisioned by Sir John Lawton’s ‘Making space for nature’ report it will be necessary to protect existing areas of habitat, ensure they are better connected, AND create new space for biodiversity – not simply replace several small sites with one big one as would be the case with offsetting. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Lawton identified that after decades of parcelling land into protected, designated sites, the country still does not have an ecologically coherent network of designated landscape and natural sites. This is precisely because of the fragmentation of complete landscapes with ‘lower value’ sites being seen as fit for development for lack of designation.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A local wildlife site may be playing an important buffer role in the wider landscape but this would not be properly valued under offsetting.  At best a crude multiplier’ would be applied requiring the  developer to 'buy' more  habitat in another location at the expense of connectivity in the existing landscape.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Developers will choose to pay for habitat in a different location over providing space for nature in new developments</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An EMTF paper on Biodiversity Offsetting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">looking at the benefits to developers suggested that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“Currently, planning authorities concentrate restoration/compensation measures within the red line boundary (the boundary of the development site which is the subject of the application for planning permission).  This reduces Net Developable Area at significant cost to the developer.  Offsetting would instead allow the developer to address residual impacts beyond the site boundary and thereby limit any reduction in NDA”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> To achieve biodiversity gain we need to incorporate biodiversity into development. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none"> This should be regarded as an important element of providing a high quality development not as a hindrance to responsible developers. Guidance produced by TCPA and The Wildlife Trusts stresses the importance of design standards to improving ecological connectivity.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">  The guidance recommends that as a general rule 40 per cent of the total land should constitute green infrastructure.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Local access to nature will be lost</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a high risk that biodiversity offsetting will fail to account for the value of natural spaces to local communities.  The Green Paper suggests that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“letting offsets be provided anywhere in England might lead to a loss in some areas of the country (e.g. where there is greatest value in development) with net gain elsewhere (e.g. areas where offsets can be secured most cheaply).  This would be both economically and environmentally beneficial”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no means of valuing the social and cultural values of access to nature in the metrics proposed for offsetting.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allowing the loss of local natural spaces in areas of high development pressure would directly contradict promises made in the Natural Environment White Paper to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“improve access to nature in local neighbourhoods, giving more people the opportunity to gain more benefits from connecting people with it”</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The most recent MENE (Monitor of Engagement with the Natural Environment) survey by Natural England concluded that  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A general appreciation of natural places was evident with 48 per cent of the population strongly agreeing that it is important to have green spaces close to where they live.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">In contrast offsetting would separate nature from people by re-locating it away from the development.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is growing evidence of the benefits of access to nature and this includes direct benefits to businesses such as reduced sick days, increasing business productivity and staff retention.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Natural England has set out Accessible Natural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Greenspace</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standards to reflect the importance of securing access to natural green space close to where they live.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By imposing a national system that doesn't take into account the value to local communities, the process will also remove the democratic rights of local communities to have a say in shaping their local area through the planning system.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Multiple benefits of nature will not be valued</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Offsetting would measure the value of nature simply in terms of the habitat that is present on the site.   Crucial ecosystem services such as pollination or climate change mitigation would not be taken into account by current offsetting proposals.  Wetlands for example are important for flood control as well as for the wildlife they support but this is not considered in the offsetting metric.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also a risk that there will be increased pressure to approve development on good quality agricultural land without consideration of its importance in food production.  This is because agricultural land will generally score poorly on habitat distinctiveness and so will be ‘cheap’ to offset.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Challenges of enforcement and possible weakening of existing legislation</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Friends of the Earth is not convinced that strong enough legislation exists to secure the offset site and ensure its on-going management to benefit biodiversity.  The Green Paper suggests that sites and requirements on how they will be managed will be secured by means of conservation covenants.  However it goes on to say that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> “the covenant could be released if, through a planning decision, it was considered developable land”.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is a significant flaw in the offsetting proposals since it means that damage to biodiversity can take place with no certainty of compensation actually being delivered.  It is difficult to see how this brings benefits over the existing system of compensation in the planning system.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Experience in Germany is that commitments to replace and manage habitats have not been properly implemented and enforcement is difficult.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensuring that any restoration or protection projects funded through an offset are additional to what would have otherwise occurred is a challenge.  The Green Paper suggests that ‘habitat banking’ should be used.  This would allow an offset provider to offer a habitat restoration or creation project in advance to ‘sell’ as an offset at a future date.  It will be difficult to determine whether such projects may have happened anyway.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodiversity offsetting is not a silver bullet to reverse biodiversity loss.  It is likely to facilitate the loss of biodiversity to development in one place with a vague promise of biodiversity creation in another place, without guarantees that it would benefit biodiversity as a whole.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The evidence is that biodiversity and ecosystems in the UK needs rapid and urgent restoration and recovery, and that is where the Government should be concentrating its efforts, especially since its progress on protecting and improving the natural environment is lagging behind the need for urgent and extensive action.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Offsetting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">does not deliver this and at best it would only offer marginal gains over existing compensation requirements when comprehensive delivery of nature is required. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Annex 1: Case Studies</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Kent: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The British Trust for Ornithology (BTO) raised concerns about an offsetting proposal in Kent where development is proposed on a site important for nightingales including the significant time delay in establishing a suitable new habitat and the difficulties of establishing and managing the new habitat.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“To maximise the chance of success a number of key considerations must be taken into account... It must be stressed that even if these are all incorporated into a habitat creation plan, the establishment and persistence of a large Nightingale population cannot be absolutely guaranteed. Meeting the requirements of the species as thoroughly as possible is especially important at a time when nationally the range of the species is contracting and the overall population is declining.”</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Gloucestershire: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gloucestershire Wildlife Trust has objected to a planning application for 100 new houses on species rich grassland.  The applicant has proposed biodiversity offsetting.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Roborough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Fields contains a rich variety of hay meadow plants which support many invertebrate species.  Some 97% of hay meadows have been lost in the UK since 1945.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Dr Colin </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Studholme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of GWT called the concept of offsetting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“fundamentally flawed”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> adding that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“First it is not possible to recreate some ancient habitat types, such as the grassland community at </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Rodborough</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Fields, and second it does not take into account the fact that a local community might be losing their much-loved wildlife area and the compensation for that loss is carried out somewhere else.” </span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Tyneside: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An application for 366 houses in North Tyneside was rejected - he Northumberland Wildlife Trust said that the loss of open farmland habitats would harm farmland birds. However when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bellway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> homes took the case to appeal the inspector overturned the decision with the support of Communities Secretary of State Eric Pickles and recommended approval. Part of the reason for the decision was the promise of an offset. The Environment Bank, a private company which has set itself up as a broker of offset sites seems to have played a key role in the decision:</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.66pt; padding-left:0.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“The Environment Bank has expressed confidence in the ability to deliver offset requirements and that there is a reasonable prospect of delivering a scheme”.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">14 October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> For example see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">PostNOte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 429 on Biodiversity and Planning Decisions </span><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/briefing-papers/POST-PN-429"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.parliament.uk/briefing-papers/POST-PN-429</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Environment Defenders Office (Victoria) Ltd, (2013) Reforming Native Vegetation Offset rules in Victoria</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Letter to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Rt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Hon Owen Paterson MP from Environmental Policy Forum, 26</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> April 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Evidence to Efra Select Committee hearing on 18th April 2012</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Note from meeting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">organised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> by British Ecological Society September 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Babtiste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, R, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Couvet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, D, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Kerbirou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, C (2013) Offsets and Conservation of the Species of the EU Habitats and Birds Directives, Conservation Biology Volume 00 No 0 1-9</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.tcpa.org.uk/data/files/TCPA_TWT_GI-Biodiversity-Guide.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.tcpa.org.uk/data/files/TCPA_TWT_GI-Biodiversity-Guide.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> HM Government (2010) he Natural Choice: securing the value of nature: page 49</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/5331309618528256?category=47018"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/5331309618528256?category=47018</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/32031"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/32031</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/biodiversity-2020-simple-guide-and-progress-update-july-2013"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/biodiversity-2020-simple-guide-and-progress-update-july-2013</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><a href="http://www.medway.gov.uk/pdf/Nightingale%20habitat%20compensation%20report%20FINAL%20_18%2010%2012.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">              </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.medway.gov.uk/pdf/Nightingale%20habitat%20compensation%20report%20FINAL%20_18%2010%2012.pdf</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.gloucestershirewildlifetrust.co.uk/news/2013/07/11/wildlife-trust-objects-rodborough-fields-planning-application"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.gloucestershirewildlifetrust.co.uk/news/2013/07/11/wildlife-trust-objects-rodborough-fields-planning-application</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://saveourwoods.co.uk/articles/nppf/biodiversity-offsetting-permits-previously-rejected-housing-development/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://saveourwoods.co.uk/articles/nppf/biodiversity-offsetting-permits-previously-rejected-housing-development/</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.15pt; text-indent:-14.15pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>